AB  - Veterinarians, veterinary nurses and allied personnel may be potentially exposed to veterinary medicinal products during the course of their work. However, such exposures, should they occur, need to be considered in context as veterinary professionals face numerous other hazards and associated risks. Of these, the major examples are physical injuries which may be animal-associated such as biting, crushing or goring, or they be of other origins and include slipping, falling and injuries associated with lifting. The most common injuries are needlestick injuries associated with the administration of injectable products. Except for pain at the injection site due to physical injury, the majority of these accidents are asymptomatic but adverse effects may ensue if the initial injury is followed by drug administration. Other hazards include zoonotic diseases, dermatoses and allergies. Some cancer types appear to have increased incidences in veterinarians. An increased incidence of melanoma may be due to skin exposure as a result of working outdoors and exposure to sunlight. However, increases in the incidences of other tumour types are more difficult to explain. It is unlikely that the use of X-ray equipment, particularly of more modern devices, contributes to this excess incidence. Veterinarians appear to suffer from a higher degree of mental illness when compared with the general population. The reasons for this are unknown but they may include the effects of working in an isolated environment, stress and work overload. Any adverse effects relating to occupational exposure to veterinary medicinal products must be seen in the wider context of occupational issues relating to work in the veterinary sector. However, this does not mean that hazards and risks should be overlooked but that appropriate mitigation measures should be considered and if necessary, acted upon.
