AB  - Fish health research has focussed almost exclusively to date on disease and the taxonomy of pathogens and parasites. Health is more than merely the absence of disease. By applying concepts adapted from veterinary herd medicine and human population health, a broader concept of fish health emerges. This concept sees health as a capacity rather than a state and deals with the ability of fish to meet their needs for daily living as well as meet our ecological and economic expectations for them. Fundamental obstacles to fish health research lie in problems we have in with studying health and disease under natural conditions. Four main themes for future research are discussed. We first need to create a shared definition of health and to develop and validate useful fish health indices. Second, efforts must be expended on developing representative and reliable methods for surveillance of health and disease under natural and cultured conditions. Third, we need to develop a conception of health and disease that is mulitfactorial in order to identify how environmental, ecological and management changes affect fish health. Finally, it should be a priority to train and support individuals who examine health holistically and collaboratively. Acting on these four themes will allow us to move fish health research from its current role as a reactive science that responds to dramatic events of death, disease and deformity towards a model that avoids all three of those outcomes and promotes health.
