AB  - This study represents the Wrst determination of lipids and fatty acids in Wsh scales. Scales collected from groups of Atlantic salmon reared on Wsh farms and in experimental tanks were analyzed by chromatography. The complete suite of fatty acids normally found in marine organisms was detected in the scales, with the following fatty acids dominating: 16:0, 18:0, 18:1n9, 20:5n3, 22:6n3 and 24:1n9. Scales contained relatively high levels of furan fatty acids, and the level of cholesterol (2.5-5 mg/g tissue) was much higher than the levels found in the edible parts of marine Wshes (0.2-1 mg/g tissue). The fatty acid proWle of scales was distinct between groups of salmon originating from diVerent commercial strains reared on the same farm, between salmon groups originating from the same strains but reared at diVerent farms, and between groups of fed and unfed salmon in experimental tanks. Together, these data indicate that the fatty acid composition of Wsh scales is dependent upon both environmental and genetic factors. The fatty acid composition of Wsh scales may be used in stock/population identiWcation, for example identiWcation of escaped Atlantic salmon to farm of origin.
