AB  - <jats:p>We predicted small-scale hydrodynamics, including the effect of the aquaculture farming infrastructure, for a region within the group of salmon farm concessions identified in the Chilean regulation as ACS-7. The geographical region corresponds to the Caucahue Channel, composed of two branches connected by a constriction on Caucahue Island, Inland Sea of Chiloe, Chilean Patagonia. The prediction methodology considers the interaction of a regional ocean model and a high-resolution local CFD model. The model prediction was validated using available data from ADCP. We find that the Caucahue Channel is characterized by a complex circulation and hydrodynamics, including an unstable shear flow, with meanders and turbulent structures, and retention zones. Results show the aquaculture infrastructure has a non-local hydrodynamic effect. Differences in horizontal and vertical velocity can be quite significant even far from aquaculture centers, reaching up to 300% and 170%, respectively, in simulations without taking its effects into account. The useful characteristics of this predictive approach and its potential use in particle tracking and species diffusion prediction allow for the use of projecting as a tool for strengthening the environmental and productive management of this industry.</jats:p>
