AB  - Recent developments in rapid digital phenotyping methods have resulted in new phenotypes in finfish aquaculture like feed intake, growth, and body fat towards improving the feed efficiency complex. Similarly, digital operational welfare indicators have been newly developed for Atlantic salmon including: the number of lice, the number and severity of wounds, condition of fins and smoltification status. The methods employed across these diverse phenotypes vary in approach but show some similarities. In general, they focus on being high throughput and non-invasive, reducing the fish time out of water by using semi-automated image or vibrational spectroscopy. All phenotypes tested were significantly heritable (0.18-0.61) and correlated to their respective gold standards (0.70-0.98). The added benefit of being either higher throughput, cheaper or less invasive than their gold standard counter parts; means digital phenotyping methods will likely continue to develop to meet the needs of future genetic selection programmes.
